^-|CP||AT|^c@2^Y@3When contract bridge was first played, back in the twenties and early thirties, it was a puzzle as to what to do with a 4-4-4-1 hand with opening count after an opponents opening bid. Obviously it could play very well. 

But in order to find a good trump suit, one really wanted to whisper across the table: "Pard, do you have a four—card suit that will match one of mine so we can make beautiful music together?" 

Anyway, back then, Britain and American had a strong  rivalry. "We invented it", You didn't", "We‘re better!" "No, we are." etc. Then at a  particularly hard-fought match which took place before a wide audience at Harrods, the department store in London, the Americans used the first takeout double to describe this problem hand.

"Foul!" cried the British. "Double must be for penalty." After a fair amount of argument and negotiation, the Americans were permitted to use the double as a takeout bid. This was the birth of the first "artificial" bid!|
