^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|A couple of minor points. First a few people asked me if Kia should open 2@C. I personally don't think so, although some people might. The easiest way to decide whether or not to open 2@C is to use the "9  trick rule." If you think your hand can take 9 tricks opposite 0 HCP in pard's hand, but average distribution in the other suits then you are strong enough to open 2@C.|
PG| ***** 51 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|In this case Kia can count 6 hearts and a diamond for sure. I would count half a club and say 1/2 a spade. That gives him 8 tricks, so he is not strong enough.|
PG| ***** 52 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The other rule is the Bergen "4 and 4 rule" which I find a lot more difficult, and people often get confused about it. Let me briefly cover it here. |
PG| ***** 53 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If your suit is a major, and you have 4 quick tricks and 4 losers, you can open 2@C. But people mess up what Bergen means by "losers." Before I explain Bergen's definition of losers, lets look at Kia's quick tricks. He has 2 in hearts, 1 in diamonds, and 1/2 in clubs which is below 4.|
PG| ***** 54 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|In terms of losers, you don't use the Klinger losing trick count method. You actually figure out how many "losers" you think you have if partner has nothing. In his hands, you can count 0 losers in hearts, because on average partner will have 2 hearts at least (there are 7 out, so on average partner will have 2 1/3 hearts). |
PG| ***** 55 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If partner has 2 hearts, and they break 3-2 you have no heart losers. So it is ok with Bergen to count 0 heart losers. Diamonds are easy. He has 1 diamond loser. Spades are more difficult, but with QJ9 you can be optimistic and say you have 2 spade losers. Nevertheless, clubs are the key.|
PG| ***** 56 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Klinger would count the clubs as 1 loser. But Bergen would call it 1.5 losers. If partner has nothing in clubs, you will lose 2 clubs half the time. So Bergen would say Kia has a 4.5 or 5 loser hand (depending on what he decided about spades). Regardless he definitely does not have a 4 loser hand using the Bergen 4 and 4 rule.|
PG| ***** 57 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Since most people find it difficult to count losers using the Bergen methodology. I suggest you use the 9 trick rule when deciding whether or not to open 2@C.|
